    <h2 class="mt-5 text-[24px] font-semibold">How does rAPId work?</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">rAPId is an open-source end-to-end solution, with API and infrastructure code included. The solution is built to be scalable, allowing users to work with big data; and secure, with the ability to control fine grained permissions.</p>
    <p class="mt-4">It’s also built to be cost-effective, with the solution’s operating cost scaling with the amount of data shared. As the solution is available open-source, users can easily deploy a working version of rAPId for themselves. Code can be found on GitHub and is open to all departments, other organisations and the public: <a class="link" href="https://github.com/no10ds/rapid">https://github.com/no10ds/rapid</a>.</p>
    <p class="mt-4">By using rAPId, government departments have been able to discover, manage and share high-impact data internally and across government. Several government departments are actively using rAPId e.g. Cabinet Office, No10, HMT.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-5 text-[24px] font-semibold">Future</h2>
    <p class="mb-2 mt-4">Work is currently going beyond rAPId to offer open-source, cutting edge cloud infrastructure (Project Condor) that will allow departments to create the infrastructure that suits their data, analytical and AI needs. The purpose of this is to reduce reliance on contractors and increasing government’s cloud expertise and capability, allowing it to better leverage data at scale.</p>

